##One person alone in a hotel, Wuhan 90 after the boss insisted on free medical care to provide accommodation

The papernews

The function introduction, has the connotation the current politics new media

Reporter from the paper, Li Siwen, intern, Hu Youmei

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Zhang Yu home to the hotel equipment cover with protective film, disinfection twice a day. Photo courtesy of the respondents

Zhang Yu's family has been alone in the hotel for 24 days, working as a receptionist and a cleaner every day. At dawn, he watched the paramedics rush away, and in the dead of night, he opened a door for the weary, the most meaningful thing he could think of right now.

On New Year's Eve, after a brief communication with his family, the post-90s Zhang Yu family decided to open the hotel, which had been closed for two days, to join the Wuhan Medical and Nursing Hotel Support Union, which provides free accommodation and services for medical staff. A week later, most of the hotels in the alliance pulled out due to exhaustion, but Zhang's family persevered, continuing to guard the 50 medical staff who had checked in.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Fruit and canned food given to Zhang Yu's family by medical staff. Photo courtesy of the respondents

One man guarding a hotel

Born in 1991, the Zhangs run a business hotel called Jinhan next to Wuhan's first hospital, within two or three kilometers of the Wuhan Union Hospital and the Fourth Hospital. On this year's Lunar New Year's Eve (January 24) , Zhang Yu's family and his family were touched by a photo of a medical worker crying under the pressure of having a meal inside a department.

"My mother said we were close to the hospital and suggested opening the hotel to medical staff and providing them with a place to rest, " Zhang said, adding that the family was very supportive of her proposal. But at that time, the hotel of Zhang Yu's family had been closed for two days, and the attendants had all gone home for the holidays. The family had a dispute over who should manage the hotel, "My father wanted to go as soon as he heard this, but I felt the youngest and most resistant, and finally decided I would take care of the shop. "

On the same New Year's Eve, hundreds of hotel industry employees in Wuhan spontaneously formed the "Wuhan Medical Hotel Support Alliance" to provide free accommodation and services to medical staff. Upon learning of the Alliance, Zhang Yu's family immediately signed up to participate. On the morning of New Year's Day, after cleaning and disinfecting the hotel, he opened the door and began receiving medical staff. Between noon and early morning, 40 Union hospital staff were admitted to the hotel.

"Some of their medical staff are far away from their homes, there is no public transport after the closure of the city, and it is not convenient to go home, and some of them are afraid of bringing the virus home and are staying in hotels, " the family told The Paper www.thepaper.cn  , most of the hotel staff are from the post-90s generation, the youngest of whom was born in 1997 and is under 23 this year.

The hotel has a total of 56 rooms, and the Zhang family provided 50 rooms for medical staff. To be on the safe side, each room was occupied by one person and was full the next day. There are medical staff check-out, Zhang Yu family will immediately clean up, disinfection, and soon there will be new medical staff to live in.

Since the opening of the New Year's Day, Zhang Yu's family has not returned home again, a person responsible for all the work of the hotel. To be safe, he disinfected hallways, handles, elevators and other public areas twice a day, using a pressure cooker and spraying dioxidochlorine(.) . The hotel is off-limits to all but medical personnel, including takeout.

There was no place to cook, and my father would bring him meals from time to time. Zhang Yu's family mostly eats instant noodles for fear that it would be unsafe for them to leave the house. Only on the Lantern Festival did he boil a pot full of Tangyuan and give it to every paramedic who checked in.

Leave a door open for the paramedics

Although the hotel rooms are almost full, but the medical staff to protect the Zhang Yu family, rarely close contact with him, a call before going out, meet a thank you, all let the Zhang Yu family very touched. "sometimes they would bring me food and often tell me how hard it was, but I didn't do anything, it was them. "

Zhang said he wears protective clothing and a mask every day to clean the room for the medical staff. Because his clothes are not breathable, even in the cold winter, his clothes will be wet through for almost an hour, "So I can feel it is not easy for medical staff to wear protective clothing every day in the hospital, " he said

As the medical staff in the room is not the same department, Everyone off-duty time is not the same. Zhang Yu's family gets up six or seven times a night to open the door for medical staff. "Many people are afraid to disturb my rest. They are too embarrassed to call me. Some people keep saying they are sorry every time they come in. "

Zhang Yu's family said that once there was another nurse who, because of leaving work too late, stayed directly in the department for a rough night in order not to disturb his rest, "I told her that day that there was really no need. Even if you didn't come back, I was used to getting up six or seven times a night. "

In order not to disturb the rest of Zhang Yu's family, someone then proposed: If you are from the same department or know someone, you can first ask in the medical care group if you are sleeping, if you can help to open the door, if there is no one to open the door, to Call Jang Woo's house. But Zhang's family felt no need. "I did this job to leave a door open for them, so that when they are tired, they can have a place to rest, and then someone will wait for them to go home. "

On January 31, the "Wuhan Medical Hotel Support Alliance" issued a notice, saying that due to the lack of urgently needed materials and financial resources, most hotel personnel have been extremely exhausted, starting from the 31st, the 159 hotels in the alliance will no longer receive medical staff and guests. But Zhang's family decided to stick with it. "Many hotels quit because they didn't know it would last that long, but I'm going to stick with it and just hope the epidemic ends soon, because the health care workers are really working too hard. "

The family has not seen their 1.5 year old son for more than 20 days since he entered the hotel on the first day of the Lunar New Year, he told The Paper. Now he wants to hold out until the epidemic is over. He can go home and play with his children in peace.

This issue is edited by Chang Chen
